Players across the world according to nationality

In [10]:
# Pie chart, where the slices will be ordered and plotted counter-clockwise:
labels = 'North America', 'Japan', 'Europe', 'Others'
sizes = [sum(data.NA_players), sum(data.JP_players), sum(data.EU_players), sum(data.Other_players)]
explode = (0, 0.1, 0, 0)  # only "explode" the 2nd slice (i.e. 'Hogs')

fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots()
ax1.pie(sizes, explode=explode, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%',
        shadow=True, startangle=90)
ax1.axis('equal')  # Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle.
plt.title('Players across the world')
plt.show()

A pairwise relationships plot, which creates a matrix of scatter plots by default. This kind of plot helps us visualize the relationship between different variables in a single output.

platform_genre_sales = data.pivot_table(
                        index='Platform', 
                        columns='Genre', 
                        values='Global_players', 
                        aggfunc=sum).fillna(0).applymap(float)
sns.heatmap(platform_genre_sales, annot=True, fmt=".1f", linewidths=.5);
plt.title('Sales of different genres according to the platforms')

In [17]:
years_data = data.groupby('Year_of_Release')[['Global_players']].sum().join(
    data.groupby('Year_of_Release')[['Name']].count())
years_data.columns = ['Global_players', 'Number_of_Games']

Global Sales vs Number of games released

In [18]:
trace0 = go.Scatter(
    x=years_data.index,
    y=years_data['Global_players'],
    name='Global Sales'
)

# Create a line (trace) for the number of games released
trace1 = go.Scatter(
    x=years_data.index,
    y=years_data['Number_of_Games'],
    name='Number of games released'
)

# Define the data array
data = [trace0, trace1]

# Set the title
layout = {'title': 'Global Sales vs Number of games released'}

# Create a Figure and plot it
fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
iplot(fig, show_link=False)
